<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> I like the ideas some people have had of reducing the effectiveness of a charmed mob. Lower it’s regen. Lower its damage output. Heck, lower its health. (Although I could see that being used to soften up a mob, then break charm and get an easy kill.)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
However almost every post before that pretty much gave the impression that you were firmly against nerfing enchanters (directly appropriating the charm skill) and that you believed its balanced. Here are a few more direct statements you made: <br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I’m so furious at the very IDEA that anyone would use the “N” word for Enchanters about this that it makes me want to puke. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Here's my view on things:<br>
- Nerfing is the worst thing you can ask to do to a class.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
At level 64 an Enchanter can charm something that allows them to do MASSIVE damage. Cool.<br>
<br>
There's risk involved, and she can't outdamage 3 of ANY class. In burst output you can find Wizards and Mages do just fine. Charm doesn't eclipse those by any means.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Charm isn't going to make anyone obsolete.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Surely you would see where one would get confused. Before you said you were:<br>
-against nerfs<br>
-believed risk keeps charm balanced, and <br>
-that enchanters are not making any classes obsolete <br>
<br>
However in your post just now you claim that you have seen the opposite in action, and that you even support ways to nerf the charm ability so that this wouldnt happen. Since you never really openly aknowledge you changed your view point that youve had through out the rest of this thread except for that 1 recent post, i hope you could understand where i would get confused. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=noonievioletskies>NoonieVioletskies</A> at: 1/9/03 8:26:30 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lordgojirax>LordGojirax</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Conjurer</span><br>  Posts: 277<br> <font color=#333333>(1/9/03 8:28:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=443.topic&index=140>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.jackntracie.com/images/gojhead.jpg width=98 height=126></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Enchanters Overpowered ?</span><hr size=1> I'm still against nerfing. Perhaps it's the word itself. I consider nerfs to be the removal or obsolescence of a spell or item.<br>
<br>
Tuning is what (Since day one) I'm in favor of.<br>
<br>
Nerf to me means to make something harmless. (Such as turn something into a Nerf ball.. harmless and fluffy.)<br>
<br>
To tune something means to bring it more in line with &quot;The Vision&quot; of game merchanics.<br>
<br>
I've always stated that I want things tuned. And I still wanna puke when I hear someone say &quot;Nerf&quot;.<br>
<br>
I also agree that I didn't understand the magnitude of the harm that CoD does to PoP encounters in general.<br>
<br>
The other argument I don't find too compelling is the &quot;They get an AA every 20 minutes!&quot;... there are so many classes that can Quad/AE and do special things. (I can't go mow down Fungus grove free of risk for instance.) I don't complain about those things, so I'm not gonna complain about Chanters getting fast exp.<br>
<br>
It does sound like some difference of opinion (But less than we started with for sure.) and some misunderstanding. The written word is a horrible form of communication, that's for sure.<br>
<br>
No worries. Take care,<br>
Goji<br>
